She takes the photographs abroad — to Amnesty, to the Russell Tribunal, to any parliament that will seat a mother holding a picture of a son the Mexican state insists was never born. The regime that survives every domestic accusation cannot survive the specific shame of being explained, in French, to people who buy its oil. Each name she reads in Geneva costs Bucareli something no budget line covers.
